==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1610s.
* From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|accrediter|accréditer}}, from {{m|fr|a|à|to}} + {{m|fr|crediter|créditer|to credit}}, from {{m|fr|credit|crédit|credit}}.
* See {{m|en|credit}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkɹɛd.ɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-accredit.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[ascribe]]; [[attribute]]; credit with.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To put or bring into [[credit]]; to [[invest]] with credit or [[authority]]; to [[sanction]].
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:William Cowper|William Cowper]]
#*: His censure will {{...}} '''accredit''' his praises.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Thomas Shelton|Thomas Shelton]]
#*: these reasons {{...}} which '''accredit''' and fortify mine opinion.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To send with [[letter]]s [[credential]], as an [[ambassador]], [[envoy]], or [[diplomatic]] agent; to [[authorize]], as a [[messenger]] or [[delegate]].
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:James Anthony Froude|James Anthony Froude]]
#*: Beton {{...}} was '''accredited''' to the Court of France.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[believe]]; to put trust in.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:G. C. Lewis|G. C. Lewis]]
#*: The version of early Roman history which was '''accredited''' in the fifth century.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Robert Southey|Robert Southey]]
#*: He '''accredited''' and repeated stories of apparitions and witchcraft.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To enter on the credit side of an [[account book]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To certify as meeting a predetermined [[standard]]; to certify an educational institution as upholding the specified standards necessary for the students to advance.
#: ''The school was an '''accredited''' college.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To recognize as outstanding.
# {{lb|en|transitive|literally}} To [[credit]].

